<font color="#FF0000">TRADING IN THE REAR!!!</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 14 16:28:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Now, you have all made me feel guilty!<br><br>
 I have some high respect for those who served in the rear. More power to them we used to say. They kept us going and we appreciated it. Often what we could not beg, borrow or steal some guy in the rear would get for us. Some provided for many our needs at great expense. <br>
But, Ice Cream?<br>
The only time I saw Ice Cream in Nam was during operation Knox. It took us two days to get off the mountain where puff had been shot down. The CO promised us Ice Cream if we reached the bottom by the second day, the Navy chopper that was bringing in the Ice Cream got snipped at twice and he didi moued out of there real quick, But there was another chopper (also Navy) who did return. Not to take a chance, he threw the ice cream down to us, of course by the time it struck the ground and we got to it, all we were able to taste was the form alongside the river's edge. Still tasted like ice cream and it's memorable to this day.<br><br>
I do feel guilty about having taken advantage of the guys in the rear on more then one occasion.<br>
I did some of my best trading with guys in the rear, used to walk away with cases and cases of beer and soda over just a few NVA K-bars. I thought they were stupid for that (sorry).<br><br>
But I still feel guilty about one incident we pulled.<br>
We went down to mammasons hooch and paid her three daughters to cut their hair which we semi-braided and sold them to some poogues in the rear at Da Nang.<br>
Told them we had cut the hair off some dead VC we had shot in battle. Heck it got us three bottles of Johnny Walker Red, one bottle of Jack Daniel's, three cases of beer and six cases of soda all for the three dollars we paid mammason.<br><br>
We all served a purpose, in the rear or in the field, one of the greatest present I received from a staff sgt in Nam was when I was going to return to my unit and he presented me with a bag full of cleaning gear and a brand new M-60 barrel. I could have kissed him that day. It was like Christmas and a Lerp package all rolled into one. I knew it had taken him a while to get all that stuff together and I still think of that Marine's dedication and willingness to help us get what we needed in the field.<br>

<p><code>-- Cookbarela@iname.com  (Cook Barela) </code><p>


